# Terminology and naming (hard rules)

Portable baseline for git automation and rule layering: `docs/agent-guidelines.md`.

These rules apply to every file in this repo. They are non-negotiable.

## Banned terms

Never add, keep, or reintroduce references to:
- `Everest`
- `ProBuilds`

If you encounter either term in any file, remove it entirely (do not replace with a euphemism) and rewrite the surrounding sentence to preserve meaning.

## Terminology corrections

- "GR ticket" and "GR" refer to **Jira design tickets**. Always write "Jira ticket" or "Jira design ticket." Never write "GR ticket" or "GR" as a standalone term for tickets.
- "Managed Services" is the old name for **ExpertOps**. Replace in all new or updated materials. On first mention, write "Percona ExpertOps" (one word, capital O). "Managed Services" is acceptable only when providing historical context (e.g., "formerly Managed Services").
- "Percona Link" is the old name for **Percona ClusterSync**. Replace in all materials.

## "Open source" (never hyphenated)

- Always write **open source** (two words, no hyphen), whether used as a noun, adjective, or verb.
- Never write "open-source."
- If you encounter the hyphenated form in any file, replace it with "open source."

## Formatting

- No em dashes (`—` or `--`). Use commas, periods, colons, or parentheses instead.
- No blockquote carets (`>`) in draft copy that will be sent as messages or pasted into external tools.

## Naming hierarchy (Percona leads)

Use the most defensible formulation available. In order of preference:

| Priority | Pattern | Example | Use where |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 (strongest) | Percona leads | "Percona Software for MongoDB," "Percona Support for MySQL" | Headlines, CTAs, section headers, first mention |
| 2 (defensible) | "for [DB]" | "Support for MongoDB," "Expert Support for PostgreSQL" | Section headers, body copy |
| 3 (weakest, avoid) | "[DB] [Service]" | "MongoDB Support," "MySQL Consulting" | Never in headlines. Acceptable in referential body copy only |

## Customer-facing product names

| Context | Use this | Not this |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Headlines, one-pagers, events, overview pages | **Percona for MySQL** (umbrella) | Percona Distribution for MySQL |
| Software detail pages | **Percona Software for MySQL** | Percona Distribution for MySQL |
| Download pages, docs, technical implementation | **Percona Server for MySQL**, **Percona Distribution for MySQL** | (These are fine in technical context) |
| Any customer-facing copy that isn't docs/downloads | **"software"** or **"stack"** | "distribution" (causes confusion: attendees hear "distributed database") |

## Canonical product and offering names

### Database products (Percona develops and maintains)
- Percona Server for MySQL
- Percona XtraDB Cluster
- Percona XtraBackup
- Percona Toolkit
- Percona Distribution for MySQL (technical name for the full bundle)
- Percona Server for PostgreSQL
- Percona Distribution for PostgreSQL (technical name for the full bundle)
- Percona Server for MongoDB (source available under SSPL, not open source)
- Percona Backup for MongoDB
- Percona ClusterSync for MongoDB (previously "Percona Link")
- Percona Monitoring and Management (PMM)
- Percona Operator for MySQL (based on Percona XtraDB Cluster)
- Percona Operator for PostgreSQL
- Percona Operator for MongoDB

### Databases Percona supports but does not develop software for
- Redis
- MariaDB (Community versions only)

Never claim Percona develops Redis or MariaDB software.
- OK: "Percona supports Redis users with operational expertise."
- Not OK: "Percona builds software for Redis."

### Generic MongoDB technology references

- Use this for broad capability statements that are not naming a specific Percona product: "MongoDB-compatible environments" or "MongoDB services monitored by PMM."
- Use exact product names for product-specific statements, for example "Percona Server for MongoDB" or "Percona Operator for MongoDB."
- Keep feature scope explicit when relevant, for example "MongoDB only" when a PMM capability does not apply to MySQL or PostgreSQL.

