## Licensing accuracy (non-negotiable)

- Only call software **open source** if it uses an OSI-approved license.
- If not OSI-approved, call it **source available**.
- If license status is uncertain, write **TODO: verify license** and default to "source available."

| Product | License type | Label |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Percona Server for MySQL | GPL | Open source |
| Percona Server for PostgreSQL | PostgreSQL License | Open source |
| Percona Server for MongoDB | SSPL | Source available (never "open source") |
| Valkey | BSD-3-Clause | Open source |
| Redis (post-2025 re-license) | AGPL | Open source |

## MariaDB scope

Percona supports **MariaDB Community versions only** under Expert Support and ExpertOps. Do not:
- Use "any MariaDB version"
- Imply coverage of MariaDB Enterprise editions under standard Support entitlements
- Claim Percona develops MariaDB software

**Support vs consulting:** Expert Support and ExpertOps = MariaDB Community in published scope. Non-Community editions, versions outside that scope, and migration programs = Expert Consulting and Services.

**Migration copy:** Prefer **controlled migration** and validation in the customer environment. Do not claim MariaDB is a drop-in replacement for Percona Server for MySQL across all versions and features.

**Product framing:** `products/mariadb/messaging.md` (no `competitive.md` for this lane unless approved later).

**Defer until product confirms:** SkySQL competitive hooks; MaxScale or Community 10.3-and-earlier matrices beyond the generic Community guardrail.

## Third-party trademark rules

- Use ® on first or prominent mention of registered marks (MongoDB®, MySQL®).
- Never pair a third-party trademark with copy that criticizes or disparages the trademark owner in the same headline, subhead, or CTA.
- **Test**: "Would this line work with a generic noun instead of the trademark?" If yes, use the generic noun.
- See `reference/canonical-naming.md` and `NOTICES.md` for full attribution.
